        "number": 8,
        "imagePath": "/oracle-images/oracle-6/8_icon.png",
        "description": "8\r\nPen\r\nGeneral\r\nNoun\r\nWriting\r\nVerb\r\nWrite\r\nAdjective\r\nWritten\r\nAdverb\r\nPermanently\r\nQuestion\r\nNo\r\nDetailed \r\nAnswer\r\nNo; things are how they are, \r\nirrevocably and immovably.\r\nSocial\r\nThe NPC you’re speaking with has eidetic, or \r\nphotographic, memory; they recall everything they’ve \r\nheard and seen with vivid detail... Including this \r\nconversation and every nuance about the PCs, should \r\nsomeone else find that information useful later.\r\nSocial\r\nRole\r\n  Asset\r\nContext\r\n  Formal Gathering\r\nChoice\r\n  Gather Info\r\nResult\r\n  Volunteers Info\r\nCombat\r\nEach time a wound is suffered from one of these \r\nenemies, it reduces the victim’s maximum hit points \r\nby 1.  This effect lasts only until the end of the combat \r\nencounter, and each victim may only suffer this effect \r\nonce per enemy creature, per round—so, for example, \r\nan enemy who hits with four melee attacks in a single \r\nround only reduces the target’s max HP by 1.\r\n  Random Encounter\r\nA bard or commoner approaches, having heard of \r\nyour exploits, and offering to take down tale of your \r\ndeeds.  Whether you send them away or embrace the \r\nopportunity, they follow, at times annoyingly, and at \r\nothers helpfully.\r\nCombat\r\nOutcome\r\n  Ability\r\nTargeting\r\n  Weakest\r\nRole\r\n  Leader\r\nRole Size\r\n  Elite\r\nStance\r\n  Cornered\r\nQuest & Encounter\r\n  New Quest\r\nYou’re called upon to take down the confession of an \r\nailing NPC of powerful stature.  In it, they confess to \r\nsomething so horrible that you may feel compelled to \r\ntake action to see justice served.  The narrator dies at \r\nthe conclusion of their confession, so any follow-up \r\nyou take must involve the scope of those affected, not \r\nthose who performed the deeds.\r\n  Quest Development\r\nYour approach to the next objective cannot be \r\nretraced; it’s a one-way path.  Perhaps the bridge \r\ndeteriorates and falls; maybe monsters or an obstacle \r\nblocks the reverse path; or it could be that magic or \r\nillusion or planar shifts make travel impossible in the \r\nother direction.\r\n  Reward\r\nA book: a memoir of a prominent NPC in the nearest \r\nlarge city.  Reading it (which takes 7 days of passive \r\nperusal during long rests) grants you insight into the \r\npolitics of the region, granting you a +1 competence \r\nbonus on social checks and Knowledge checks related \r\nto the culture, power structure, militia, or factions of \r\nthe area.\r\n  Penalty\r\nSomeone produces a confession to a terrible crime, \r\nsigned in ink or blood by one of the PCs.  The party \r\nassumes it is a forgery, and perhaps it is, but though \r\nthe PC’s comrades might believe them, the forces of \r\njustice in the city do not.\r\nQuest\r\nArchetype\r\n  Mystery\r\nSub\r\n  PCs, P.I.\r\n11"
