        "number": 13,
        "imagePath": "/oracle-images/oracle-6/13_icon.png",
        "description": "13\r\nDesk\r\nGeneral\r\nNoun\r\nWork\r\nVerb\r\nWork\r\nAdjective\r\nWorking\r\nAdverb\r\nFastidiously\r\nQuestion\r\nYes\r\nDetailed \r\nAnswer\r\nYes, but it will require a lot of \r\ndifficult work.\r\nSocial\r\nIt’s difficult to get this NPC’s attention, because they’re \r\nalways working.  Obsessive is one word for it; successful \r\nis the one they would likely prefer.  This distraction is \r\nunpredictable in terms of effect; each social check, there is a \r\n  1 in 3 chance that it grants you a +3 circumstance bonus \r\nto that check, a \r\n  1 in 3 chance that it applies a -3 penalty, \r\nand a \r\n  1 in 3 chance that you roll normally.  Once you land \r\none \r\n  critical failure or two ordinary failures, this NPC \r\ndeclares the conversation over, as you’re wasting their time.\r\nSocial\r\nRole\r\n  Acquaintance\r\nContext\r\n  Formal Gathering\r\nChoice\r\n  Gather Info\r\nResult\r\n  Answers\r\nCombat\r\nThese foes are on a job, and focused on that much moreso \r\nthan the diversion of fighting you.  Each round, roll a \r\n  \r\nd20 and add the number of creatures your enemies have \r\nlost to the fighting; on an 18 or higher, they decide that they \r\nmust be on their way, and withdraw.\r\n  Random Encounter\r\nA solicitor greets you, and demands your presence in court \r\nin the nearest city.  It seems you have been accused of \r\nsomething terrible—tax evasion, perjury, theft, or something \r\nup to and possibly including murder.  They leave you with an \r\nofficial-looking parchment and a date and location to appear. \r\nYou know that you’re innocent, but ironically, the only way \r\nto prove it to a court is to break into a prominent NPC’s \r\nresidence or business and steal receipts, ledgers, or other \r\ndocuments which prove that they were the ones guilty of the \r\nmalfeasance.  A moral conundrum, perhaps, for some parties.\r\nCombat\r\nOutcome\r\n  Ability\r\nTargeting\r\n  Farthest\r\nRole\r\n  Leader\r\nRole Size\r\n  Elite\r\nStance\r\n  Relentless\r\nQuest & Encounter\r\n  New Quest\r\nA patron asks something humble but challenging: work \r\nat their facility.  Select a profession or crafting skill at \r\nrandom; that is this patron’s industry, and the work that \r\nthey require you to undertake.  It may or may not be a skill \r\nthat any PC has proficiency with; nevertheless, the patron \r\nwishes your involvement.  Trained workers are rare, and \r\nthey have immediate need to fulfill commitments.  Should \r\nthe PCs complete their task, each gains the lowest level of \r\nproficiency in the skill involved if they don’t already have \r\nit, or one free skill rank in that skill for systems that use \r\nthat approach.  This benefit is in addition to other normal \r\nrewards.\r\n  Quest Development\r\nYour next step involves performing a task: select a random \r\nprofession or crafting skill.  If you don’t have that talent in \r\nyour party, you’ll need to convince or hire someone to help.\r\n  Reward\r\nAn hourglass paperweight wrought of brass and inlaid \r\nwith gemstones.  The jewels are fake, and add nothing \r\nto the device’s value, but it is imbued with magic: when \r\nupended, the person closest to it receives \r\n  advantage \r\non Profession and Craft related skill checks, and rolls any \r\nnumerically-variable results from those checks (e.g., number \r\nproduced, value) with \r\n  advantage, while the sand pours.  \r\nThe device may only be used for a total of 100 hours before \r\nits magic is exhausted forever, but these hours need not be \r\ncontiguous.\r\n  Penalty\r\nCourts find the party guilty of some minor crime; the punishment \r\nis manual labor of a kind suited to the skills of those involved.  Pick \r\na Profession or Craft skill amongst those in which the PCs are \r\nproficient; the party as a whole must spend at least a fortnight’s \r\nworth of total time engaged in that discipline, but it may be split \r\namongst party members if feasible (e.g., two PCs who each have the \r\nsame skill may halve the time to a week).\r\nQuest\r\nArchetype\r\n  Obtain\r\nSub\r\n  Find\r\n16"
